Deaths in Rhode Island Hospitals

Liam Mahler

Identifying Deaths in the Data Set

The field dispub92 is the final disposition of the patient

  • 8 values refer to a patient “expiring”
  • 20 = Expired
  • 21 = Expired-Autopsy
  • 22 = Expired in O.R.
  • 23 = Expired-Post O. R.
  • 24 = Expired/Coroner
  • 40 = Expired at home
  • 41 = Expired in a medical facility
  • 42 = Expired, place unknown

Deaths Compared to Overall visits by Age

  • Deaths make up a small number of the overall visits and in most cases are so infrequent that they don't have a noticible impact on the graph
  • As age increases we begin to see a higher number of visits and a much higher number of deaths

Primary Payer by Age

  • As age increases, we see that medicare becomes the dominant form of payment for patients in RI hospitals

Deaths By Month and Sex

  • In general, there are less hospital visits in RI during the summer

Admtype vs Asource

  • Almost all admtype 4 are asource S, this is because they are all babies with type and source coming from being a new born

Average Age of Expired Patients vs Non-Expired Patients by Quarter

  • Here we can see that patients who die are on average about 20 years older than those who do not

LOS of Expired Elderly Male and Female Patients who have and have not been admitted to the ICU

  • It is interesting to see that a large number of the dead patients have a long length of stay and were admitted to the ICU

Most Frequent Payers by Month and Year

  • We see that medicare is by far the most used payment plan by far, but RIte Care also has a large number of users
  • the distribution seems to stay the same throughout, which is good for the models

Most Common Payers for Male Patients

  • Many of the levels of “payer” are nearly zero and are unlikely to provide significant predictive power
  • 3 of the levels (medicare, Blue Cross, and RIte Care) are more than double the next largest level

ICU Visits by Year and Month

  • ICU assignment seems to be highly variable by month
  • There does seem to be a trend developing with the repeated curves of the graph

Outcomes of ICU patients by year and month

  • Compared to the age graph from the beginning, we are beginning to see noticible groupings of expired patients when ICU visits are included

Modeling Death

Prework for Building the Model

set.seed(1738)
dfmodel<-df%>%
  filter(yoa>15)%>%
  filter(sex==1 | sex==2)%>%
  mutate(icu=as.numeric(icu))%>%
  mutate(yearmonth=paste(yoa, moa, sep="-"))%>%
  mutate(icuFlag=case_when(icu == 0~"No",
                           TRUE~"Yes"))%>%
  filter(admtype==1|admtype==2|admtype==3|admtype==4|admtype==5)%>%
  filter(payer!="Y" & payer!="Z" & payer!="X")%>%
  filter(asource!="X" & asource != "V" & asource != "U")%>%
  select(target=death, icuFlag, yearmonth, age, sex, raceethn, provider, admtype, asource, service, payer, drg)%>%
  drop_na()

library(caret)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(dfmodel$target, p = .70, list = FALSE, times = 1)
train <- dfmodel[ splitIndex,]
test <- dfmodel[-splitIndex,]

library(ranger)
train0 = train[train$target == '0',]
train1 = train[train$target == '1',]
n0 = nrow(train0)
n1 = nrow(train1)
train00 = train0[sample(1:n0, n1),]
train_under = rbind(train00, train1)

The 5 Models

  • Random Forest
  • Decision Tree
  • Logistic Regression
  • LMT
  • Neural Network
